	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />That's not a big deal. Just repair the broken trace and make sure there are no shorts. I think radio shack sells a pen for such a task. That or just carefully solder a piece of wire across the gap.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Memblers</b> [ Thu Nov 09, 2006 12:30 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Or rather than try to bridge the gap, find another point that the trace leads to that's easy to solder to.  For the other end you could scape the solder-mask off of the top of the connector pin and wire to that, but if you put it back in a case you'll need to cut a little notch in the case.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>blargg</b> [ Thu Nov 09, 2006 12:51 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Here's a page I made many years ago, describing how to repair a broken circuit board (I once repaired a computer keyboard like this with a crack all the way down the center). The technique is the same for bridging over a broken trace (if ever you are intentionally breaking a trace with plans to later re-bridge it, do it next to a solder hole so you don't have to use any wire to re-bridge it).
<br />
<br /><a href="http://www.io.com/~greens/temp/repair_circuitboard/" class="postlink">Repairing Broken Circuit Boards</a>
<br />
<br />In summary, use a single strand from stranded copper wire and scratch the coating off the circuit trace to solder on to it.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

